{"/service/ndnp/wa/batch_wa_columbia_ver01/data/sn88085947/00211108587/1908030401/0289.xml":{"full_text":"4\nSURE IN IT BUSINESS\nIS AGAIN ON UPGRADE\nBY GILSON GARDNEER.\nWASHINGTON, D. C, March 4\nBusiness is on the up-grade. Rail\nroad revenues have begun to im\nprove.\nFor the first time since the panic\n\u25a0truck in November have there been\nany figures in the government re\nports forecasting an early return of\nprosperity. Now there are such\nfigures. The improvement in rail\nroad earnings is undeniable.\nExperts in railroad accounts have\none figure which they watch as in\ndicating the run of railroad busi\nness. This figure is the \"total o]>-\nerating revenue\" in pro pot ion to\nthe \"total number of miles oper\nated.\" Long experience has shown\nthat the \"normal\" revenue of a\nrailroad is about $1000 a mile.\nThus the normal return of the\n222.000 miles of railroad, making\nreports to Washington, would be\n$222,000,000. If the total operating\nrevenue shows larger than this the\nmonth is an abnormally good\nmonth. If it is less the month is\nan abnormally poor month.\nThus, the month of October, 1907,\nwas an abnormally good month,\nand the total operating revenue of\n222.000 miles of road reporting was\n$245.000,000.\nThe month of November showed\nthe effects of the panic; but not ihe\nfull effects. For that month 921,000\nmiles of road reporting showed\n$218,000,000 revenue.\nThen came December with the\nworst returns, namely 188.000 miles\nof road reporting $157,000,000 rev\nenue.\nThe reports for January are not\nall in. but enough mileage is at\nhand to show that the January\nrevenues, instead of decreasing,\nhave begun to pick up. The per\ncentage of Improvement will prob\nably be found to be considerable\nwhen the returns are all available.\nBut the main thing is that the turn\ning point has been passed, and the\nrevenues are on the uii-grade.\nAll of which is of the highest im\nportance in view of the fact that\nrailroad officials are threatening to\nreduce wages, alleging decreasing\nrevenues as the impelling cause for\nsuch decreases.\nAnother very important indica\ntion of the condition of business is\nthe cheapening of money. Reports\ncoming to the controller of the cur\nrency shov: that the national banks\nare now glutted with money. The\nrate on \"call loans\" in New York is\nless than 3 per cent.\nBut more significant than the\nrate on \"call loans\" is the fact that\nall the national banks are now\nclimbing over one another to re\ntire their bank note circulation.\nThe law frliids the retirement of\nthis circulation on any rate more\nrapid than $9,000,00(1 a \"month. This\nlimit has been reached in applica\ntions for February, March and April.\nAttention has been called in\nsome quarters to the sudden in\ncrease in our exports. For Janu\nary, 1908, they were $208,000,000, as\ncompared with $199,000,000 in Jan\nuary of 19u\". December exports\nDRIVE OUT THE JAPS\nViHLYXED<\u00a3.FeL\u00a3NQ; \u00abci,mo -vwhx< io.OOO <Jat><\u00ab True\nSpecial Correipondtace to The Freis\nFRESNO, Cal., March 4.\u2014Con\nvinced that the welfare of them\nselves and their posterity depends\nupon immediate and aggressive ac\ntion, the Federated Trades Council\nof Fresno has begun a campaign the\npurpose of which is to eliminate the\nJap.\nAlthough American labor knew\nthat the struggle was inevitable,\npresent events bring the matter to\na white heat.\nAt a meeting of the Federated\nTrades it was decided to ask the\ndepartment stores to discharge their\nJap help. This information, con\nveyed to leading Japanese on the\ncoast, brought a delegation of\nprominent Japs from San Fran\ncisco. Formal protest was made\nand threats were made to report\nthe case to the Mikado's govern\nment.\nThe delegation was frankly ln\nfrmed that the fight had only be\ngun. A few days later one of the\nmembers of the Ministerial Union,\nwhich Is affiliated with the Feder\nated Trades, urged prompt action\nAt the suggestion of the ministers\na resolution was adopted asking\nproprietors of all the stores to stop\nemploying Jap help.\nAll department stores, with one\nexception, discharged their Orien\ntal help, In eight saloons Jap\n\u2022jortera were discharged.\nAgain a Jap delegation arrived\nwere also $17,000,000 above the pre\nvious December.\nThis Is a healthy and good condi\ntion, but it does not necessarily in\ndicate prosperity at home. On the\ncontrary it means that the home\nmarket does not absorb the manu\nfactures and they are forced to look\nabroad for a market.\nCorresponding to the increase in\nexports is a decrease in im\nports. In December imports\ndropped to $92,000,000, as com\npared with $134,000,000 in De\ncember of the previous year, and\nin January to $86,000,000 as com\npared with $127,000,000 of the year\nbefore. Which means that the\nscarcity of money during those\nmonths found its reflection In the\nsmaller amount of goods bought\nabroad. Of course this decrease af\nfected the tariff revenues of the\ngovernment.\nMerchants and manufacturers\nwere holding orders and waiting\nto see what would happen. In the\ncourse f 60 days more it will be\nseen that confidence has largely re\nturned an dthat orders have even\nnow commenced to go forward.\nTRUITT DENIES\nREWARD CLAIM\nHere's another misunderstanding\nover the Stotko reward. Yesterday\nAttorney A. M. Winston filed a\nclaim for the $1000 with the city\nclerk in behalf of J. C. Truitt.\nTruitt today made affidavit that\nstatements that he had filed a claim\nwith the city for the $1000 reward\nare false and misleading. He makes\noath that he never authorized any\nsuch claim, has no claim of any\nkind on the reward nor has per\nformed any service that would jus\ntify such claim.\nTruitt was a friend of Libby Mor\ngan, who revealed Dalton to the\npolice. Mr. Winston states that\nTruitt put the claim in his hands\na year ago in company with the\nMorgan woman. He says he has no\nintention of going farther if Truitt\ndoes not care to. And Truitt swears\nthe whole thing is false.\nSENTENCED IN B. C.\nThe police have been informed\nthat J. R. Harding, who victimized\na lot of people of Coeur d'Alene\nwith bad checks, has been sen\ntenced to two year; in the peniten\ntiary for his depredations at Ross\nland. B. C, where he was captured\nand tried.\nWHITMAN SETS DATES.\nWALLA WALLA. March 4\u2014April\n30 and May 1 have been announced\nas the dates for the athletic and\ndeclamation contests at the invita\ntion of Whitman college. For the\npast eight years Whitman has in\nvited the best schools in the Inland\nEmpire of Washington, Idaho and\nOregon to participate in the con\ntests.\non the scene and asked that their\ncountrymen be re-empioyea. They\nasked to see a copy of the consti\ntution of the Retail Clerks' Union,\nwhich does not discriminate against\nwhite labor of any kind. The Japs\ncontended that they were white,\nand therefore should not be objects\nof discrimination. The clerks' union\ninformed them, however, that they\ndid not class Japanese as white, and\nso the second delegation returned\nnorth, after having succeeded only\nin fanning the flame.\nIn discussing the plan of cam\npaign, Secretary T. C. Seaward of\nthe Federated Trades said: \"We\nthink the time is ripe for beginning\naction which will not be ended until\nwe have won the fight. In Fresno\ncounty there is a working Japanese\npopulation of at least 10,000. Our\nidea is to work through the state\ncentral organization of labor. The\nplan will be successful If laboring\nmen, farmers and merchants unite.\nIt is planned to have the producers\nand the merchants send to the\nstate bureau of information statis\ntics on the amount of labor needed,\nand to have the bureau collect In\nformation as to the number of\nwhite men they can secure from\ndifferent parts of the country. In\nthis way the supply and demand\ncan be accurately gauged. We\nthink next summer will witness a\ngreat change In the local Japenese\nsituation.\"\nUSE ELEPHANTS AS STRIKE BREAKERS\nSpecial Correspondence to The Press\nRANGOON. India, March 4\u2014At\nPenang, on the Malay peninsula,\n700 miles south of Rangoon, the\nBritish India ship Barhata took on\nfive distinguished passengers Jan.\n11. Thhe came to the ship waving\npalm branches and carrying their\nfood (palm leaves) on their backs.\nThey were Youseff, Ibraham,\nRam, Lai and Bon. Youseff was\nold, Ibraham a mere youth of 50,\nRam, Lai and Bon, being of the\nsofter sex, did not disclose their\nages. Youseff announced their com\ning with loud trumpetings and\nleading the other four elephants on\nboard laid down his burden of palm\nbranches on the forward deck and j\nhis companions piled their burdens\nneatly on top. This big pile of palm\nleaves served as the only food for\nthe elephants on their three-day\njourney to Rangoon.\nIbraham, not so accustomed to\ntravel as Youseff, felt of everything\nwith his trunk. Finally he laid\nhold of an iron stanchion. To his\nsurprise if did not move. He put\nanother twist of his trunk around\nit. settled back on his haunches,\nripped up the 1500-pound stanchion\nand a small section of deck, waved\nhis trophy in the air several times,\nwhile the crowd about him and his\nelephant companions trembled and\ncrouched, then threw the stanchion\n50 feet into the sea, trumpeted\nloudly and subsided.\nThen the Indian boys surrounded\nhim, hobbled him with chains and\nOHIO FOR TAFT ON A\nROOSEVELT PLATFORM\nCOLUMBUS, Ohio. March 4\u2014The\nrepublican convention today adopt\ned a platform dictated by Taft's\nfriends. It represents Roosevelt's\nideas. On national affairs it de\nclares for a square deal, law en\nforcement, industrial liberty, indi\nvidualism, government regulation,\nemployers' liability law, compensa\ntion to injured government em\nployes, injunction limitation, great\ner merchant marine waterways.\nSAY THEY WILL FORCE\nSUNDAY LID WARRANTS\nThe Sunday closing tangle today\nis more of a tangle than ever. On\nMonday Attorney Alex M. Winston\napplied for 17 warrants against\nvarious places of business for viola\nting the Sunday closing ordinance.\nJustice Hinkle, t owhom the appli\ncation was made, and before whom\nthe complaints were signed, took\nthe matter under advisement. Ow\ning to the prosecution supposedly\nbeing brought about through the\nalleged revenge of some Main avc.\nclothiers who were arrested and\nconvicted for keeping open on Sun\ndays, on complaint of a member of\nthe clerks' union, there is doubt if\nthe justice will issue warrants at all\nunless forced to do so by mandamus\nproceedings, which, it is said, will\nbe brought by Attorney Winston.\nJustice Hinkle this morning stat\ned that he would announce tomor\nrow what he decides to do about It.\nIf the warrants are refused\nJustice Hinkle will then be in a pe\nculiar position. The question is\nthen what will he do if the Main\naye. clothiers keep open next Sun\nday and warrants are asked for\nthem.\nIt is announced that the clothiers\nwill open up next Sunday.\nThe clothiers are unable to ac\ncount for the court's action In is\nsuing warrants for them without\ndelay when the clerks' union made\ncomplaint, and yet delaying action\nwhen the clothiers bring a similar\nSPOKANE PRESS, WEDNESDAY, MARCH 4, 1908.\ngave Youseff in eight-foot length of\nchain.\nIbraham In his helpless state was\nsoundly whipped by YousefT, who\nswung the heavy chain with his\ntrunk, and brought It down with\nsuch force that Ibraham's back was\ncovered with welts. He howled\nlustily, dropped great tears of\nagony and at the end of five min\nutes, much bni'sed and humiliated,\nhe was loosened and behaved like\na lamb the rest of the voyage.\nThe five elephants were on their\nway to Rangoon to work in the teak\nlumber yards.\nA big drove is used in Rangoon\nto handle the big teak logs which\nweigh from a thousund pounds to a\nton each.\nIt takes two years to train one\nelephant to this work, when he is\nworth $5,000; but as the beasts live\nto be 150 to 180 years old the train\ning is well worth while.\nThe telephants lift the logs, lug\nthem to the sawmill, where they\nare cut into timber, and then the\nelephants put he timber in square\npiles. It is the most amazing thing\nto see these elephants lay a timber\non theh pile, take a sight along the\nedge to see if it is straight, and if\nnot push or pull it into place with\ntusk and trunk.\nCaptain Nelson of the Bahata, a\nmere Englishman without a joke in\nhis system, said he brought the\nPenang elephants to Rangoon to\nbreak up an elephant smke In one\nof the Rangoon lumber yards. The\nharbor improvements, revision of\ntariff by a special congress, reduc\ntion of representative in congress in\nstates disfarnchising negroes, and\nrush work on Panama canal.\nIt indorses Taft's candidacy and\nmentions his genius for world\npeace. Unanimous support of na\ntional delegates instructed.\nForaker is completely unhorsed,\nlosing the last of his support on the\ncentral committee by last night's\nelection.\ncomplaint on the identical offense\nfor which they were arrested and\nfor which the law provides the same\npenalty.\nThe clothiers further claim that\nthey are actuated by no motive of\nrevenge but take the position that\nif the law is to be enforced there\nshould be no discrimination under\nthe law.\nNext Sunday night the newly or\nganized nest of Owls will commit\nits first offense by giving an open\nmeeting to which the general pub\nlic Is invited. A spread of sand\nwiches and salads will be laid out.\nA vaudeville program has been se\ncured.\nSenior A class of the high schol\nyesterday selected Alva Kitt, Ar\nthur Hedlund, Randall Pratt and\nMiss Marie Prahinska to represent\nthe class at the commencement\nnext June. The orators selected by\nthe faculty are Miss Sadie Collins,\nCharles Newbury, James Ppofford\nand Miss Ella Verke.\nMrs. Helen Wood, landlady of the\nMonica hotel, notified the police\nlas tnight that about 10 o'clock a\nyoungish looking man. dressed in\ndark clothes and wearing a dark\nslouch hat, passed a bad bill on\nher and received $4.1.) in change.\nHe did not come back to occupy the;\nroom he rented.\nelephants refused to work, except\nbetween the hours of 7 and 9 a. m.\nand 3 to 5 p. m. They made an\nawful row, too, if they did not get\ndouble allowance at their noon\nmeal, and it was with a view to\nbreaking up this condition of affairs\nthat the Penang elephants with the\npowerful and sagacious Youseff at\ntheir head had Oeen brought in.\nCaptain Nelson, growing dis\ncursive, said: \"What if the elephant\nhad made a crafty resolve and had\ndetermined to stand on his hind\nlegs some aeons ago as man did?\nThen the elephant, which Is the\nonly animal except man and the\nmonkey whose knees bend forward,\nwould have outstripped us.\n\"He would have stood on his\nhind legs as we do, developed his\n'fore paws into hands and developed\nhis brain, which is five time as\nlarge as ours.\n\"Then he would have had his\ntrunk in addition, to grasp and hold\nwhat his hands could not clutch.\n\"Let us thank God that the ele\nphant did not think of standing up\nstraight, else we might have been\nhis slaves and waiting his orders in\nstead of jabbing him with a gad\nand making him work for us.\"\nOn theh first day when the Pa\ngoon elephants saw the new gang\nfrom Penang working through the\nheat of the day they bent to with\na will, as if to say, \"We can stand\nas much as you can.\"\nWhat they did the second day we\ndo not know, for we sailed away to\nCalcutta on a smart turbine\nsteamer. Thus does the west stamp\nitself on the east. The turban and\nthe turbine together. Soon the tur\nban will disappear.\nThe elephant, too, with all his\nstrength, is no match for steam and\nthe engine cannot only beat him\nlifting, but has no need to rest in\nthe heat of the day.\nHATCHED PLOTS\n111 JAIL\nScott Yarnell, the fourth of the\nstreet car holdups, was captured in\nTacoma yesterday on advice sent\nfrom this city. He will probably\nbe brought here by Police Chief\nRice, who is after the fifth of the\ngang in Portland. He has not re\nported success.\nThe plot of the car and pedestrian\nholdups was hatched in the county\njail by Scott Yarnell and the fifth\nbandit, while they were serving\nsentences. Yarnell was arrested\nNov. 6 by Patrolman Pheland on a\ncharge of stealing razors from\nMohler's barber college, and was\nsentenced to serve a $100 fine. Soon\nafter his release Patrolman Pitts\narrested him on suspicion of rolling\na drunk. A conviction could not\nbe secured and the police ordered\nhim to leave the city.\nOPEN TOWN BIRDS\nFLOCK TO SEATTLE\nA general exodus of \"sports\"\nfrom Spokane Is soon to take place.\nThe prospective destination is Se\nattle, where yesterday the open\ntown element won the election by\nan overwhelming vote. With the\nClancys again in the ascendancy,\nthat town will be wide open and tho\nold regime of gambling and out\nlawry will no doubt result.\nTHREW AWAY HIS $80\nBen Smith of the Nagel hotel was\nabsente minded enough this morn\ning to leave his vest behind. He\nwent back a few minutes afterward\nand met a stranger coining out. The\nstranger was smiling and evidently\nwell satisfied. Smith eagerly\nsearched the pockets of the vest in\nwhich when he left it hanging there\nwas $80. The money was gone,\nhowever, and therein Smith says he\ncan explain the satisfaction of the\nstranger.\nGood Watches\nLow Priced\nWe are making excep\ntionally low prices, in fact\nabout cost, to reduce our\nstock of fine timepieces.\nNo old or unknown move\nments, but the latest and\nbest Waltham and Elgin\nwatche\u00df. Try us.\n7 jewel Waltham... .$4.60\n7 jewel Elgin $4.50\nIB Jewel Elgin $5.50\n15 Jewel Waltham $5.50\n17 jewel Elgin $7.50\n17 jewel Waltham $7.50\nC. E. BTURGES\nWatchmaker, Engraver\nand Jeweler,\n813 RIVERSIDE\nParisian Dye Works\nHas no branch offices nor\nagents. Office 60S tirst Aye.\nPhone 2137. L. A. .ehmann\nThe Regal Shoe\nS7 WASHINGTON\nHutton Block\nVOYAGE OF THE PULO WA V\nWILL BEGIN TOMORROW\nHere is a scene from \"The Voyage of the Pulo\n\"Way,\" a story of marine adventure in the South seas.\nIt will be run in serial form in The Press beginning\nwith tomorrow's issue. Romance and adventure are\nblended and the work breathes the atmosphere of the\nopen sea. Care has been taken to avoid purely blood\nthirsty scenes that would excite repulsion. It's a\ngood story and you want to read it.\nI Eyeglasses Spectacles\nCOME TO US IF YOU\nWANT GLASSES\nFITTED CORRECTLY\nIf your eyes burn; if you are troubled with head\naches, dizziness, near or far sight, double or blurred\nvision, you probably need glasses.\nCome to us to be fitted. We are expert opticians.\nWe have fitted thousands with glasses and specta\ncles. You have the benefit of our many years of ex\nperience. We have every instrument known to the\noptical world for examining eye errors. We save\nyou half. Try us. We guarantee all our work.\nOur Scale of Prices\nUntil March 10\nWill Be\nAll gold filled frames, warranted 5 years, <tO C A\nwhite crown crystal lense, not over y6\u00abDU\nAll rimless nose glasses, including finest full length\nchain, warranted 10 years, with lens AC (1 A\nspecially ground, from \u00abf>3 CO *p Ivl\nAll rimless gold filled spectacles, mountings guaran\nteed 10 years, with best quality d?C Rf*l\nlenses, from <pOIO \u00abpf >uU\nFirst class Bifocal work proportionately low priced.\nNotice to the Public\nWe have been crediably Informed that some person, or per\nsona, are peddling spectacles In the city of Spokane and are\nclaiming-to represent this office. We desire to state that we\nhave no canvassers, and that all such persons are Impostera.\nIf you desire to take advantage of our special prices for the\nnext ten days come to our offices, be examined by an expert\nand be convinced that your eyes can be properly fitted with\nreading or distance glasses.\nPacific-American Optical Co.\nManufacturing Opticians\nRooms 22-23 Ziegler Block. Phone Riverside 121.\nOffice Hours 8:30 a. m. to 5 p. m. Lady Attendant.\nSpokane Press 25 Cents Per Month\nCLOTHING\nBILLS\nWon't Worry\nYou\nIf you take advantage of our\nHttle-at-a-tlme plan, for then\nthe expense is so distributed\nthat you hardly miss the\nmoney.\nWe cordially Invite you\nto open an account with us\nfor anything selected from\nour splendid stock of down\nto-date Summer Apparel for\nMen and Women \u2014you'll And\nour styles Invariably correct,\nour prices \"right\" and our\nmerchandise absolutely de\npendable in quality.\nNew goods arriving by\nevery express\u2014we'll be de\nlighted to show you.\nEASTERN\nOUTFITTING CO.\n422 SPRAGUE AY.\nSPOKANE'S RELIABLE\nCREDIT HOUSE\nFIRE\nThe orders for your coal Into\nPHONE 3333\n\"Summer prices In the winter\ntime.\"\nROCK BOTTOM\nBridger Lump, per t0n....58.50\nBrldger Nut, per ton $8.00\nTaber Lump, per ton $8.50\nSmith Lump, per ton $8.50\nSheridan Lump, per t0n...58.75\nSheridan Egg, per ton $8.50\nSheridan Nut, per ton $8.50\nlx\u00bbthbridge Lump, per t0n..58.75\nWoodpecker Lump per t0n.58.50\nBTEAM COAL\nper ton $6.25 to $6.75\nPatronise the big\nCOAL\ncompany and save money. Qual\nity Is guaranteed first class.\nAll coal\nSCREENED\nat the yard before delivery. We\nwant your steady patronage.\nUnion Fuel Ice\nCompany\n114 Stevens St. Phone 3333.\nBlack\nDiamond\nCoal\nLUMP REDUCED TO\n$8.00\nA Clean, First-Class Coal for\nFurnace, Range and Heater\nWashington Coal\nCompany\nPhone 2248. 810 HOWARD\nThis ad. worth\n$1.00 for new\nglasses Examin\nation free. One\nprico to all.\nLANG A SON\nManufacturing Opticians\n1003 Sprague Aye., near Monroe.\nSAM CROW\nHOUSE\nFURNISHING\nCO.\n227-2$ Rlv. Ay.\nPhone 2194.\nWe are now showing\na new line of\nParlor Tables\nIn all sizes and designs that\nplease at $1.35 and up to $14.50.\nAlso a new line of Folding\nBeds from the plainest bed in\nhard wood at $15.00 up to $50.00.\nBEBT VALUES OFFERED","height":"27448","width":"23432"}}
